05937nam a22008175i 9789048555208DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20242024ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485552087 a10.1515/97890485552082doi  a(DE-B1597)673107  a(OCoLC)1414456435  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aBF575.S35 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a362.8804aThe Cultural Construction of Safety and Security :bImaginaries, Discourses and Philosophies that Shaped Modern Europe /ced. by Jan Oosterholt, Gemma Blok. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (278 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- tSection 1 Philosophical Conceptualisations of Safety -- t1 Security, Certainty, Trust -- t2 Tolerance: A Safety Policy in Pierre Bayle's Thought -- t3 The Shackles of Freedom -- tSection 2 Security Cultures in History -- t4 The Invention of Collective Security after 1815 -- t5 Criminal, Cosmopolitan, Commodified -- t6 Tourists, Dealers or Addicts -- tSection 3 Narratives and Imaginaries of Safety -- t7 The 'Golden Age' Revisited -- t8 Safety as Nostalgia -- t9 Brace for Impact -- tSection 4 Narratives and Imaginaries of Unsafety -- t10 Safe at Home? -- t11 The Transfer of Nineteenth-Century Representations of Unsafety -- t12 Feeling Lost in a Modernising World0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis volume analyses cultural perceptions of safety and security that have shaped modern European societies. The articles present a wide range of topics, from feelings of unsafety generated by early modern fake news to safety issues related to twentieth-century drug use in public space. The volume demonstrates how 'safety' is not just a social or biological condition to pursue but also a historical and cultural construct. In philosophical terms, safety can be interpreted in different ways, referring to security, certainty or trust. What does feeling safe and thinking about a safe society mean to various groups of people over time? The articles in this volume are bound by their joint effort to take a constructionist approach to emotional expressions, artistic representations, literary narratives and political discourses of (un)safety and their impact on modern European society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHuman securityzEuropexHistory. 0aPublic safetyzEuropexHistory. 0aSecurity (Psychology)zEurope. 4aContemporary History. 4aCultural Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aInterdisciplinary Studies. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aSafety, cultures of security, cultural studies, study of emotions.1 aAliaga, Ana Alicia Carmona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaptist, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlok, Gemma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlok, Gemma, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBänziger, Peter-Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBüttner, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDam, Frederik Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvink, Eddo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiesbers, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraaf, Beatrice de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKok, Femke, econtri